  "prompt": "Why does friction act in forward direction in case linear acceleration is less than product of angular acceleration and radius?",
  "response": "The concept you're referring to is typically encountered when analyzing rolling motion, such as that of a wheel or a ball. Let's break it down:\n\n1. **Linear Acceleration (\\(a\\))**: This is the acceleration of the center of mass of the rolling object.\n2. **Angular Acceleration (\\(\\alpha\\))**: This is the rate of change of angular velocity.\n3. **Radius (\\(r\\))**: The distance from the center of the rolling object to the point of contact with the surface.\n\nFor a rolling object without slipping, the condition \\(a = \\alpha \\cdot r\\) must hold. This means that the point on the circumference of the rolling object that is in contact with the surface is momentarily at rest relative to the surface.\n\nIf \\(a < \\alpha \\cdot r\\):\n\n- This indicates that the center of mass of the rolling object is not accelerating fast enough compared to its angular acceleration.\n- The point on the circumference in contact with the ground is trying to move backward relative to the surface at a speed faster than the linear speed of the center of mass.\n\nTo maintain rolling without slipping:\n\n- Friction must act to oppose this relative motion at the point of contact.\n- In this case, friction acts forward (in the direction of motion of the center of mass) to increase the linear speed of the center of mass and reduce the relative backward motion of the point of contact.\n\nThus, **friction acts forward** to ensure that the rolling condition without slipping (\\(a = \\alpha \\cdot r\\)) is satisfied and the object rolls smoothly.",
